The goal of this assingment is to obtain a model to predict the price (in Singapore dollars) of the diamonds using several variables and to improve it by solving the possible typical issues.

1.- Predicting price or log(price)?

In order to see which variable is better to be predicted we will do some basic scatter plots of both variables.

p1 <- ggplot(diamantes, aes(x=Carats, y=Price))+geom_point(color = 'darkblue')+ ggtitle('Carat vs. Price')
p2 <- ggplot(diamantes, aes(x=Carats, y=log(Price)))+geom_point(color ='darkred') + ggtitle('Carat vs. log(Price)')
grid.arrange(p1, p2, ncol=2)

The result we can infer from this plot is that it is not pretty clear wich variable is the better to be predicted. We can see that maybe log(price) is a little bit more linear to carats than price but we can assure it by using:

simple1=lm(diamantes$Price ~ Carats, data = diamantes)
summary(simple1)[8]
## $r.squared
## [1] 0.8925084
simple2=lm(diamantes$log_ ~ Carats, data = diamantes)
summary(simple2)[8]
## $r.squared
## [1] 0.9355391

So, from now on we will be using log(Price) since the R-squared coeff is closer to 1.

2.- Linear Model with Categorical Variables.

To include the categorical variables we have in our dataset we have to make reference states and then perform our model.

diamantes$Colour_purity = relevel(diamantes$Colour_purity, ref="I")
diamantes$Clarity = relevel(diamantes$Clarity, ref="VS2")
diamantes$Institution  = relevel(diamantes$Institution, ref="HRD")

model1 = lm(log_~Carats + Clarity + Colour_purity + Institution, data = diamantes)
summary(model1)

We get the output of each category as if it was a variable. The carats dependence is several times stronger than all categories and we can see than most of the Betas (\(\beta\) from now on) are possitive. Since an increment of this \(\beta\) is related with a direct increment on the log of the price, we can see that the best color purity the highest is the log(price) with a 4 times bigger growth with best purity (D) than the worst one (H). Same thing happens with the rest of categories.

Another thing we can observe is that all the p-values are low enough (pv < 0.05) to reject the null hypothesis that says those \(\beta\) are equal to 0, except for the GIA institution. The p-value of the whole model is low enough to accept this lineality on the model, in fact, the Multiple R-squared which is the common metric of linear models is pretty good since it is very close to 1. This coefficient is calculated by using covariances between the target variable and the model and with their standard deviations. The utility of using the lowest level of each variable as the base category is in order to get the \(\beta\) > 0, otherwise if you for example use the highest value of the categorical variable you will get the same absolut value of the Bs from the categories but with a different sign (-, in this case).

For the first outlier, the 110 we can see that the price seems to be overrated. The second one has a rather low price and for the last one seems to ve a little bit underrated, too.

Related to the residuals plots, since it is a model that has more than 1 explanatory variable is not that easy to understand the residuals plots as it is in a one variable linear model that can be analysed with just a simple plot.

Variance of the residuals does not seem to be constant but we can not be sure just by looking at the plots. Lets perform the Breusch-Pagan test that has an initial hypothesis constant variance of the residuals:

bptest(model1)
## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  model1
## BP = 47.223, df = 12, p-value = 4.265e-06

The low p-value rejects \(H_0\) so our variance of the residuals is not constant.

Now, we will check the autocorrelation of the residuals with the Durbin-Watson test which has the null hypothesis that the autocorrelation of the residuals is 0 which is not given its low p-value:

dwtest(model1)
## 
##  Durbin-Watson test
## 
## data:  model1
## DW = 0.31422, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true autocorrelation is greater than 0

Residuals seem to follow a rather normal distrubution:

resid=residuals(model1)
fv=fitted(model1)
ggplot(diamantes, aes(x=fv, y=resid))+geom_point()+geom_text(label=rownames(diamantes))

Let us check this assumption with the jarque-bera test.

jarque.bera.test(resid)
## 
##  Jarque Bera Test
## 
## data:  resid
## X-squared = 8.0626, df = 2, p-value = 0.01775

But jarque-bera test denies this assumption. Now it is time to try some remedial actions.

3(a).- Remedial Actions

Firstly, we have to create a new categorical variable based on the size of the diamonds and small will be the reference category.

diamantes$carat_2 <- 0
diamantes[diamantes$Carats< 0.5,"carat_2"] <- "small"
diamantes[diamantes$Carats>= 0.5 & diamantes$Carats< 1.0 ,"carat_2"] <- "medium"
diamantes[diamantes$Carats >= 1.0,"carat_2"] <- "large"
diamantes$carat_2 = as.factor(diamantes$carat_2)
diamantes$carat_2 = relevel(diamantes$carat_2, ref="small")

And now we compute the model with an interaction term:

model2 = lm(log_~Carats + Clarity + Colour_purity + Institution + carat_2 + carat_2*Carats, data = diamantes)
summary(model2)

We can observe that we have achieved a higher value of the R-Squared coefficient so a priori the model is better now. My intuition made me think that this was not going to improve the model because we have just created two variables out of the ones we already had so there was not going to be new information in the model. But I was wrong. But we still have to make an analysis of the residuals.

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(model2, which=c(1:4), ask=F)

And we will perform the same tests as we did in the model before to try to understand what has changed.

Variance, autocorrelation and normality of the resiudals:

bptest(model2)
## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  model2
## BP = 60.618, df = 16, p-value = 4.117e-07

jarque.bera.test(resid)
## 
##  Jarque Bera Test
## 
## data:  resid
## X-squared = 1.3424, df = 2, p-value = 0.5111

The results of the test show autocorrelation so they are not independent with a non constant variance and showing normality in the distribution. So the model has improved related to the study and the residuals and in terms of variance explanation as the root mean squared coefficient suggests.

The interaction term may seem a little confusing since one would expect that the larger a diamond is, the higher the priceis, and both interaction terms are negative.

In order to evalute which variable is more important to decide the price of the diamonds between colour or clarity since they are both categorical variables we can calculate the average value of the \(\beta\) values of the categories. Purity has clearly a bigger value than clarity, so we can conclude than it is more important for the model.

The differences in terms of purity, since I is the lowest category and D is the best one with a value of \(\beta \approx 0.44\) we can say that the difference in prices is a factor of \(\exp(0.44)\). The comparison with the purity E is similar, but since the diff is lower (0.44-0.36) we can say that a diamond D is 1.12 times more expensive than a diamond with category E. We can do this too, by modeling the response variable without the log function and, the difference in price will be just the difference in \(\beta\).

Related to the instituion analysis, we have same things as before but there is the IGI with a negative value of the \(\beta\) so the difference of prices with IGI will be higher than the difference between the other ones. Once again one should get the factor of difference between them, as a example: \(\beta_{GIA} - \beta_{IGI} \approx 0.18\) so the price of GIA is approx 1.18 times bigger than IGI. Since \(\beta_{GIA}\) has a pretty low value the price will be very similiar to HRD diamonds.

4.- Which model is better?

Both of the models have a very nice R-squared coefficient very close to 1. Related to residuals the model of the square of the caratage achieves homocedastic residuals but none of the models have indenpendent residuals. In my opinion the second remedial action is better because it is more easy to be interpreted and understood since the interaction term is not that trivial for me, eventhough the clustered model seems to be more accurated with just a simple clasification of the variable. The simple, the better.
